* including 694 ruminants, 398 foxes, 253 cats, 465 dogs
** including 1,113 foxes, 807 cattle, 357 cats, 515 dogs
During 1968 to 1998, 28.8 percent of human rabies cases were acquired from
red foxes, 24.2 percent domestic dogs, 7.5 percent cats, 3.8 percent
raccoon dogs and 3.5 percent wolves.
Two human infections were acquired from bats during 1965 to 1995. The agent
was European bat Lyssavirus (EBL) biotype 1.
Four rabid bats were reported during 1977 to 1995.
Six rabid bats (_Myotis daubentonii_) were identified in caves in
theNovosibirsk region of southwest Siberia in 2002 (accounting for
one-third of bats tested). The circulating rabies virus in this area is
the classical genotype 1.
